Project: Problem Statement - Personal Loan Campaign Modelling¶

Thera Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Data Description:¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Domain:¶

Banking

Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Attribute Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any.
  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Learning Outcomes:¶

Exploratory Data Analysis Preparing the data to train a model Training and making predictions using a classification model Model evaluation

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Conclusions:¶

  1. There are 5000 rows and 14 columns in the data set
  2. 13 columns have type int64 and 1 column has type float64
  3. There are no null values in the data set
  4. There are incorrect imputations in Experience column: some values are negative ranging from -1 to -3. Only customers in their 20s have negative Experience values. Taking into account their young age and small absolute values of the negative experience values, we can assume that these customer either don't have work experience or their work experience should be a positive number with the same absolute value. There are 52 such rows, which is ~1% of total number of customers and ~11% of customers of age 29 and younger.

Columns "Personal Loan", "Securities Account", "CD Account", "Online", "CreditCard" have 2 values: 0 or 1. We don't need One Hot encoding for these columns. Column "Education" has 3 values: 1, 2, 3. We need 3 One hot encode columns for this column, one of which will be dropped before regression model calculation. Column "ZIP Code" has 467. Number of customers living in a specific ZIp Code ranges from 1 to 169. We would need to create 467 one hot encode columns for regression model which can lead to model overfitting. Before continue we want for group zip codes to larger areas based on their first to digits. For example zip codes 94598, 94087, 94305 will be in 94xxx area, while 90095 and 90068 will be in 90xxx area.

In [187]:
accuracy    = (tp + tn) / total
precicion   = tp / (tp + fp)
recall      = tp / (tp + fn)
specificity = tn / (tn + fp)
f1_score    = 2 * (recall * precicion) / (recall + precicion)
